g::from_utf8_lossy(&all.stdout).contains(\\\"opencode-desktop already configured\\\"),\\n            \\\"{}\\\",\\n            String::from_utf8_lossy(&all.stdout)\\n        );\\n\\n        let undone = run(\\n            &home,\\n            &capture,\\n            &desktop,\\n            &[\\\"with\\\", \\\"--undo\\\", \\\"opencode-desktop\\\"],\\n        );\\n        assert!(\\n            undone.status.success(),\\n            \\\"{}\\\",\\n            String::from_utf8_lossy(&undone.stderr)\\n        );\\n        assert_eq!(std::fs::read_to_string(&config).expect(\\\"restored\\\"), original);\\n        std::fs::remove_dir_all(root).expect(\\\"cleanup\\\");\\n    }\\n}\\nEND_SOURCE\"\n    command \"cat tests/issue_762.rs\"\n  verification_command \"cat tests/issue_762.rs\"\n\nLearned standing requirement (create): Create a minimal Rust integration regression test at tests/issue_762.rs for issue 762. The missing feature is a distinct formal-ai with opencode-desktop target, separate from the existing opencode CLI. On Unix, create a fake desktop executable that captures arguments and environment. Invoke the formal-ai binary with: with --no-start-server --base-url http://127.0.0.1:18080 opencode-desktop. Set a proposed FORMAL_AI_OPENCODE_DESKTOP_BIN override to the fake executable so the test is portable. Assert the baseline currently fails because opencode-desktop is unsupported. Structure the final desired assertions so that once implemented it verifies: the fake native app launched; it received no CLI run or model arguments; FORMAL_AI_API_KEY is formal-ai-local; OPENCODE_CONFIG and OPENCODE_CONFIG_DIR point to temporary isolated config; the JSON includes provider formalai using @ai-sdk/openai-compatible, baseURL http://127.0.0.1:18080/api/openai/v1, apiKey {env:FORMAL_AI_API_KEY}, model formalai/formal-ai; and the users ~/.config/opencode/opencode.json was not modified. Also add one global test proving with --global opencode-desktop merges that provider into ~/.c